{
  "$schema": "https://opencode.ai/config.json",
  "mcp": {
    "youtrack": {
      "type": "remote",
      "url": "https://agile.sensory-minds.com/mcp",
      "enabled": true,
      "oauth": false,
      "headers": {
        "Authorization": "Bearer {file:/Users/Viktor/.config/opencode/secrets/youtrack-token}"
      }
    }
  },
  "command": {
    "news": {
      "description": "Summarize incoming git changes or recent commits.",
      "template": "Summarize git news for the current repository. If the user supplied a numeric argument, summarize the last that many commits on the current branch. If no argument was supplied, fetch remote refs if needed and summarize changes available to pull from the upstream branch without modifying the worktree. Start with a brief summary of the most interesting changes. Then list changed files, with one or two sentences describing what changed in each file. Keep the whole response concise. Each file needs to be in new list element and its description is next line for better readability. Argument: $ARGUMENTS"
    },
    "pr-describe": {
      "description": "Summarize this branch vs a source branch into a short, scannable PR description.",
      "template": "Sum up the changes on the current branch compared to the source branch `$ARGUMENTS` to produce a short PR description. If `$ARGUMENTS` is empty, default to the repo's main branch (`main` or `master`, whichever exists) and note which one you used. The goal is something easy to scan, surfacing only the most important info, not an exhaustive list of every change. Steps: 1. Resolve refs: run `git rev-parse --abbrev-ref HEAD` for the current branch name; determine the source branch from `$ARGUMENTS` if given, else `main` or `master`; verify it exists with `git rev-parse --verify`; if not found, report and stop; compute the merge base with `git merge-base <source> HEAD`. 2. Gather the diff scope using the merge base, three-dot, so unrelated commits on the source branch do not pollute the description: `git log --oneline <source>...HEAD`, `git diff --stat $(git merge-base <source> HEAD)...HEAD`, and `git diff $(git merge-base <source> HEAD)...HEAD` for important files. 3. Identify the important changed files, meaning the ones that carry the actual change. Skip noise like lockfiles, generated output, formatting-only churn, and trivial one-liners unless they are the point of the PR. 4. Output only the description below, with no preamble and no closing remarks. Output format: `### Summary`, then a short human-readable explanation of why this PR exists and what it accomplishes in 1-3 sentences or a few bullets, focusing on intent and outcome rather than mechanics. Then `### Key changes`, with one bullet per important file or tightly-related group in the form ``path/to/file` — one or two sentences on what changed there and why it matters`, ordered by importance. Rules: keep it tight and scannable; describe intent and impact, not a line-by-line restatement of the diff; do not invent reasons; if motivation is not clear from commits or diff, describe what changed without speculating; static review only; do not run tests, commit, push, or modify files."
    }
  }
}
